                "ph": {
                    "@keyref": "companyfirst",
                    "#tail": "sources and related Web content.\n\nIt\u2019s as easy as 1, 2, 3.\n\n\nEnter search terms in the Search box. \nChoose how to restrict your results. \nSelect the Search button.\n\n \nAs you enter search terms, New Lexis analyzes them and offers suggestions.\n\nSearch terms can include connectors (such as \"and\", \"or\", \"near\"). You can find information about connectors in this Help topic.\n\nTo"
                },
                "i": {
                    "#tail": "\u00ae a citation, enter \"shep\", followed by a colon, followed by the document citation, for example, shep: 800 f.2d 111.\n\nYou can use the links at the bottom of the search box to limit search results to specific:\n\n\nContent types\nJurisdictions \nPractice areas and topics\n\n \nThen select the Search button to run your search.\n\nAny limitations you set remain in effect for subsequent searches.\n\nYou can use the Search Assistant to enter or add to your search terms by selecting the Search Assistant link at the bottom of the search box. Use the drop-down list to select the relationships between terms, then enter the terms in the search field. \n\nSelect the \"Add to search\" button to add terms, then select the \"OK\" button to run the search.\n\nYou can also run a search you saved to a folder or from the search history. These are listed in the \"My Workspace\" area of the search form. Just select the search you want to run.\n\nThis concludes the \"Searching with New Lexis\" tutorial.",
                    "#text": "Shepardize"
                },
                "#text": "Searching with New Lexis\u00ae. \n\nNew Lexis\u00ae lets you easily search"
